comment: Wass also had the nerve to talk about how a woman's statement should be enough and that all of Johnny's witnesses should be disregarded because abuse is done in private and no one would ever really know in order to witness it...right. First, not all abuse is done in private. I saw a guy getting sexually harassed right in front of me and if I hadn't helped him figure out he needed to get the balls to stand up for himself, God knows what else she would've done. She and I were actually good aquatintences until that moment, so I'm not going to show favoritism. His excuse for not wanting to stop her even though he was notably very uncomfortable and clearly strong enough to push her away is because our society has such a strong protection for women that if he pushed her away, he could get accused. I told him, he still needed to defend himself and he had witnesses, including me, and I'm a female. So, guys get abused just like gals and not all abuse is private. Secondly, even if it IS done in private, there will either always be physical evidence leftover from physical abuse or a person's character can be identified easily. One of my abusers acted wonderful and like a great guy in public, he even had us fooled that he was great around children, that he just had a way about him that kids loved him. My sister and I, her a kid and me becoming and adult at the time, also fell for it. Obviously, as I stated, we saw his true colors and he abused us. We had never actually seen his interactions with children before then, we just took his word for it because he had two children if his own. Later, my sister, would have friends over or just MEET him. He was polite, of course, and no harm was done in front of them, but still, EVERY SINGLE KID/friend that my sister would have meet this abuser, all said the same thing: He freaked them out. They were never harmed, never witnessed harm, and he seemed polite enough, but all said there was something about him they were uncomfortable with and they didn't want to come over to the house anymore. Indeed, most abuse (again, not all) is done privately, but an abuser can still be spotted even in their personality, the way they carry themselves, and in certain things they say. "Abuse is done in private," and "Amber should be believed because she's a woman," are not good reasons to disqualify and discredit ANY of Johnny's witnesses.
